-Alternatively, you can also build the library and example using Flatpak and then start it like so:
+You can also use [flatpak-builder](https://docs.flathub.org/docs/for-app-authors/submission#before-submission) to build the library for you and install the `.mo` files for i18n:
 
 ```shell
-flatpak-builder --force-clean --force-clean --user --repo=repo --install builddir page.codeberg.puregotk.MyLibGtkMesonExample.json
+$ flatpak run --command=flatpak-builder org.flatpak.Builder --verbose --force-clean --keep-build-dirs --user --ccache --compose-url-policy=full --repo=repo builddir --install page.codeberg.puregotk.MyLibGtkMesonExample.json
+$ flatpak run --command=flatpak-builder-lint org.flatpak.Builder manifest page.codeberg.puregotk.MyLibGtkMesonExample.json
+$ flatpak run --command=flatpak-builder-lint org.flatpak.Builder repo repo
+$ flatpak run page.codeberg.puregotk.MyLibGtkMesonExample
+```
 
-flatpak run page.codeberg.puregotk.MyLibGtkMesonExample
-```
+We're disabling the sandbox here because otherwise we can't acccess the Go cache on the system.
 
 If you want to import the custom widget from Go, you'll have to generate bindings to the custom library using puregotk. For an example of how to do that, see [../mylib-gtk-meson-go](../mylib-gtk-meson-go/).
